{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"08a8e9a4-37ed-4816-a6d5-34b20b984efa","content":"Here's what needs to change:\n\n1. **Remove** the old assembly reference (`Microsoft.VisualStudio.QualityTools.UnitTestFramework`)\n2. **Replace** `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk` with the unified `MSTest` v3 package (includes framework, adapter, and SDK)\n3. **Update `TargetFramework`** — MSTest v3 dropped .NET Framework support; minimum is `net6.0`\n\nYour test code (`[TestClass]`, `[TestMethod]`, `Assert.*`, `[Timeout]`) is already compatible — the namespace is unchanged.\n\nWant me to apply these changes?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"80f690c7-4f6b-4486-88bb-e18515dc4356","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has:\n\n1. A `.csproj` targeting `net462` with:\n   - An old assembly reference to `Microsoft.VisualStudio.QualityTools.UnitTestFramework`\n   - `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk` 17.5.0\n\n2. A test file using `Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestTools.UnitTesting` namespace with `[TestClass]`, `[TestMethod]`, `[Timeout]`, and `Assert` calls.\n\nTo upgrade to MSTest v3:\n\n1. **Remove** the old assembly reference to `Microsoft.VisualStudio.QualityTools.UnitTestFramework`\n\n\n2. **Replace** the test SDK with the `MSTest` meta-package (v3+), which bundles everything needed, or manually add `MSTest.TestAdapter` and `MSTest.TestFramework` separately.\n3. **Update the target framework** — MSTest v3 requires at least .NET 6.0, so the current `net462` targeting won't work; I need to check if there's a way to keep the older framework or if upgrading is necessary.\n\nActually, MSTest v3 dropped .NET Framework support entirely and only supports .NET 6.0 and later, so the user will need to update their target framework from `net462` to something like `net6.0` or `net8.0`. They'll also need to remove the old assembly reference to `Microsoft.VisualStudio.QualityTools.UnitTestFramework` and replace the test SDK package.\n\nThe good news is that the namespace and test attributes remain unchanged - `using Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestTools.UnitTesting;` still works, and all the familiar decorators like `[TestClass]`, `[TestMethod]`, and assertions like `Assert.AreEqual` continue to work without modification. Let me apply these changes now.","outputTokens":808,"requestId":"583B:31143A:165859D:17B3DCF:6A045FD8"},"id":"1b4c52eb-a83e-4078-9504-c5b954bbfc3d","timestamp":"2026-05-13T11:26:32.013Z","parentId":"1b25ae11-d51e-42fa-a497-cb0dea119559"}
